                On April 26, 1937, hell broke out over the town of Guernica, the historical and cultural center of the Basque Country. At about 4:30 pm, a two-hour bombardment of the city by the German Condor Legion began. It was followed by a massive fire that turned Guernica into ruins. According to various sources, the bombing claimed the lives of several hundred to several thousand people. Most frightening of all is the fact that most of the victims were women and children, since the bulk of the male population at the time was involved in the fighting in the Spanish Civil War.
                The tragic news from his homeland could not leave Picasso, who has repeatedly declared his political apathy, indifferent. At that time, the artist was working on a canvas for the Spanish Pavilion at the upcoming World Exhibition in Paris. Upon learning about the bombing of Guernica, the artist instantly changes his concept and takes on a new canvas, which has become one of the most powerful artistic and political statements in history.
