                Pablo Picasso, arguably the greatest artist of the 20th century, is best known for two reasons. Firstly, for the invention - together with Georges Braque - of cubism and collage, and secondly, for his anti-war position, expressed in various works of art. Both of these moments come together in The Weeping Woman, one of Picasso's most famous portraits of analytical cubism, but with more realism than usual.

                This painting is an iconic example of Spanish painting. It continues the anti-war theme that the artist began in his epic work Guernica (1937), which became his reaction to the bombing of civilians during the Spanish Civil War. After completing the painting, Picasso spent many months creating a series of images of crying women, the prototype of which was one of the figures in Guernica. The Weeping Woman from the Tate Gallery is the latest and most challenging of the series. Others are kept in such major institutions as the National Gallery of Victoria in Melbourne, the Picasso Museum in Paris, the Los Angeles County Center for the Arts, and others.
